{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1d30c758-65c9-452b-87ac-5e3456ec73f2","content":"Here are the issues I found:\n\n1. **`targetFramework` default invalid** (line 10): `defaultValue` is `\"net7.0\"` but the only choices are `\"net8.0\"` and `\"net9.0\"`. The default must be one of the defined choices.\n\n2. **`maxRetries` default not an int** (line 24): `defaultValue` is `\"abc\"` but `datatype` is `\"int\"`. Should be a numeric value like `\"3\"`.\n\n3. **`computed1` missing `value`** (line 26–28): A `computed` symbol requires a `value` property with the expression to evaluate.\n\n4. **`generated1` missing `generator`** (line 29–31): A `generated` symbol requires a `generator` property (e.g., `\"guid\"`, `\"now\"`, etc.).\n\n5. **`postActions` missing `actionId`** (line 34–36): Each post action needs an `actionId` GUID to identify the action type (e.g., `\"210D431B-A78B-4D2F-B762-4ED3E3EA9025\"` for restore).\n\n6. **`shortName` is `\"restore\"`** (line 5): This conflicts with the built-in `dotnet restore` command and may cause unexpected behavior.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"23e8676f-bd78-486d-8ace-c09e72ca3370","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me analyze this template.json for issues:\n\n1. **`shortName`**: \"restore\" — this is a reserved/built-in command name in dotnet CLI (`dotnet restore`). Using it as a short name could cause conflicts.\n\n2. **`defaultValue` for `targetFramework`**: \"net7.0\" — but the available choices are only \"net8.0\" and \"net9.0\". The default value doesn't match any of the defined choices.\n\n3. **`defaultValue` for `enableLogging`**: \"yes\" — for a `bool` datatype, the valid values are typically \"true\" or \"false\". \"yes\" might not be parsed correctly (actually, dotnet templates do accept \"yes\" as a bool value... let me think... I believe the valid boolean values in dotnet templates are: true, false, yes, no. So \"yes\" should be fine actually).\n   \n   Looking further, I see several more problems: `maxRetries` has a default of \"abc\" when it should be numeric, `computed1` is missing its required `value` property, `generated1` lacks the required `generator` property, and the post action is missing the `actionId` that identifies which action to run. The template also lacks an `identity` property for proper identification and appears to be missing `sourceName`.\n\nFocusing on the clearest issues: the `defaultValue` \"net7.0\" isn't in the allowed choices, the int parameter has a string default, `computed1` and `generated1` are incomplete, the post action is missing `actionId`, and the `shortName` \"restore\" conflicts with the built-in `dotnet restore` command. Though I should note that bool parameters in the .NET template engine do accept \"yes\"/\"no\" in addition to \"true\"/\"false\", so that particular value is actually valid.","outputTokens":843,"requestId":"9C17:4FC4C:1C87937:200675C:6A07C05B"},"id":"b3374902-711d-42f9-a5a0-d67c7d280782","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:55:08.860Z","parentId":"b24e4a85-934f-4bc3-a149-e734963cbb02"}
